# Notion work protocol

Notion is the source of truth for work. Cursor executes; GitHub holds PRs; Ops Terminal only renders Notion.

## Start

1. Open the **Notion task URL** (required). Fetch the page; do not invent scope from chat alone.
2. Treat the task’s **Agent prompt** as the source of truth for what to build. Use Goal / Acceptance criteria / Description as supporting context.
3. Set Status → **In progress** when you begin. Fill **Repo** / **Branch** when known.
4. Branch: `cursor/notion-ops-<task-slug>` (one PR per Notion task).

## App runtime env (hard constraint)

Ops Terminal app runtime may use **only**:

- `NOTION_API_KEY`
- `ACCESS_PASSWORD`

Do **not** add GitHub tokens or other secrets to the Next.js / Vercel app. GitHub Action secrets stay in GitHub only. Optional Redis is infra, not a required app secret.

## While working

- Keep Notion in sync: short progress notes on the task (what shipped, what’s left).
- Put the **Notion task URL in the PR body**.
- Fill **PR** and **Repo** on the Notion task when the PR exists.

## Status rules (code tasks)

| Event | Notion Status |
|-------|----------------|
| Started | **In progress** |
| PR opened | **Review** (if that option exists; otherwise leave **In progress** and note the PR) |
| Merged / accepted | **Done** — only then |

Never mark **Done** just because a PR is open. Docs-only or non-code tasks may go **Done** when acceptance criteria are met and no merge gate applies.

## Completion report (required)

When finishing a task (PR open or handoff), report **all** of these:

```text
Summary: <what shipped and why>
Files changed: <paths>
Tests: <ran / skipped + result>
PR: <url or n/a>
Next action: <merge / follow-up / blocked on X>
```

Also mirror the useful bits onto the Notion task (PR link, progress note, next action) so the terminal and humans stay aligned.
